item.title: An Introduction
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Here I sit. This month I turned 28 years old and I find myself single, with three children and a mortgage. I've been blessed. So freakin' blessed. I love my boys and I love my career. I love my friends and family and the church community that God has plopped me right into. But I don't have it all together. I'm broken. So freakin' broken. Part of my brokeness is my inability to manage my finances, my time, my belongings. My house is often a wreck in between slight moments of impeccability. My yard is a jungle of weeds. I find it hard to get ahead on that never ending to-do list I keep between my ears. And I blow cash like it's air. Confession: In June 2013, I grossed over $9000 from my freelance web design business. Holy freakin' cow! How much do I have left of that? Nada. Zip. Zilch. Where did it go? I still have over $5,000 worth of credit card debt, close to $20,000 in car debt and almost $180,000 in house debt. Oh yea, and I still owe the government for part of my freshman year at a pricey private college. What is going on? The answer? My emotions are guiding my spending and how I'm managing my life. I'm burnt out. I'm spent and therefore, I'm spending my money to mask my exhaustion. We eat out. Like, a lot. I buy my kids nice toys. Like, really nice toys. I'm embarrassed at how much I spend on their clothes and toys to make myself feel better - like I'm somehow a good mom for making sure their clothes are top boutique brands and their toys are wooden and educational. Now, there are some ethical reasons there - like buying US made and sustainable products. But mostly, I just do it to make myself feel better. I need a change. This month, my oldest is starting Kindergarten and I can't won't send him to public school. Since I really do need to work full-time, it isn't reasonable for me to homeschool him any longer and so I've registered him to attend the local Montessori school. I see this as an investment. But, if I'm going to afford it, I need to make changes. Serious changes. My bank account is empty and this week I must make my first tuition payment and the mortgage. Let's just see how that works out. In addition, I have long-term goals that are never going to happen if I don't start saving for them. These are lofty goals, but I'm putting it out there and seeing where I end up:
  • Not only pay for Ronnie's Kindergarten year, but also save to pay for his 1st grade year in advance ($7,500)
  • Save for a rainy day ($12,000)
  • Pay off the debt ($28,000 without the house)
  • Make some upgrades to the house like hire a painter to fix my hack job and replace floors and doors ($7,000 ballpark)
All totaled, that's $54,500 worth of savings I need to make happen. How long will it take?

item.title: August Goals
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
This month has to be extreme. Thankfully, my fridge and cabinets are full and the boys have no serious immediate needs. My main concerns this month are paying for back-to-school costs and saving as much as I can. Each day, I'll check in here and account for any money coming in or out. I need to hold myself accountable. This month, these are the rules I'll try to stick by:
  • No restaurants. Only exception is work days when the kids are with their dad.
  • No new clothes, toys, or home decor.
  • Limited grocery budget of $50/week - an extreme cut-back for us.
  • 1 tank of gas has to last the whole month, so basically we'll keep the driving down to YMCA trips, church, and school.
  • Cancel all subscriptions and look for ways to save anywhere I can.
